Highlights

  • Elo is moderately correlated with gmpu (\(\rho = 0.55, *p* = 1.931e-09\))
  • Elo is more strongly correlated with the number of times a level was left unsolved (\(\rho = 0.398\)) compared to GMPU (\(\rho = -0.012\))
  • Elo scores are more strongly correlated with the mean duration to solve a level (\(\rho = 0.766, *p* < 2.2e-16\)) than GMPU (\(\rho = 0.629, *p* = 7.227e-12\))

Whats in the dataset

I specifically define variables are they are being introduced, but I want to make especially clear the scope of the log data. The log data for Before/After is what I have been pulling from Learning Locker over the last year. I have made various large (>3gb) downloads to ensure I always had the more accurate and comprehensive snapshot of what is in Learning Locker. Last month I took a day to merge all the copies that I had and ensure there were no duplicate values. The current log file I use runs from 05-10-2019 to 04-19-2021.

Elo Ratings

The Elo scores are created by updating the score every time a player solves or fails to solve a level. In other words, the Elo algorithm runs through the list of observations. When a player solves a level, the Elo is decreased for that level and the players Elo is increased. Elo scores start at 1500 and move up or down based on the results.

Elo assumes that performances (i.e., chess matches) are random. Players can play better or worse, but overtime the distribution will be normal. Therefore, our use of Elo for determining level difficulties is dependent on data collected over time. The more gameplay data we can collect, the more accurate our difficulty ratings are going to be. This is why, even though the studies differ, we use data from both the Big Study (linear, adaptive, and control conditions) and the Before/After study.

Given Elos assumption of random normal distributions, its worth checking if the scores we found were normal. The histogram below is of Elos cores. The center line is the mean and the left and right vertical lines are +/- 1 SD from the mean. Thats pretty normal. If there is any skew it would be a mild positive skew as fewer players to beat the hardest levels.

level_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(elo)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 100) +
  labs(
    title = "Histogram of Elo Scores",
    x = "Elo Scores") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(elo))) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(elo) + sd(elo))) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(elo) - sd(elo))) +
  geom_text(aes(x = 1750, 
                y = 20, 
                label = paste("Mean: ",round(mean(elo),2)))) + 
  geom_text(aes(x = 1750, 
                y = 17.5, 
                label = paste("SD: ",round(sd(elo),2))))

Relationship Between Elo and Physics Expert Ratings (GMPU)

The GMPU scores are expert ratings of level difficulty. Physics experts, researchers, and designers played the levels and scored them based on how difficult the level was to complete using the four different simple machines (e.g., lever, pendulum, etc.). There are separate ratings for each machine, but in the current version either the max or an average score is used. Overall, most levels have little variation in their GMPU scores (i.e., most have the same level for all machine). Cleaning up the average scores for each is on the to do list, but we need to find more complete records of those scores

To date, we have a few variations. Im still trying to find a small number of levels GMPU, so there are missing data points. However, those levels are not ones being used recently or in the near future. The levels still missing GMPU scores are:

  • UFO2
  • You Again! only played once ever
  • Swamp People only played once ever
  • Wedge only played twice ever
  • Lead the Ball

A simple scatterplot is shown below. I included as many labels as possible, but space is limited. Notice how, within each GMPU level, there is a good deal of variation among Elo scores. That could be indication of misalingment between the two measures, or the variation might indicate GMPUs lack of precision. For example, the difference in GMPU between Little Mermaid (GMPU = 4) and Green Apple (GMPU = 6) is relatively small. But in terms of Elo scores,

level_data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = elo, y = gmpu, label = level)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_label_repel(max.overlaps = 5) +
  labs(
    title = 'Relationship between Elo and GMPU',
    x = 'Level Elo Score (based on both studies)',
    y = 'Expert Ratings (GMPU)'
  )

There is a linear relationship between the two, but it doesnt seem all that strong. Because GMPU is ordinal, I used Spearmans Rho below to test the correlation and found a correlation of \(\rho\) = 0.51, p = 3.73e-08.

cor.test(level_data$elo, level_data$gmpu, 
         method = c("spearman"), 
         use = 'complete.obs') ## Use complete.obs removes NA observations
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  level_data$elo and level_data$gmpu
## S = 86262, p-value = 3.73e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##       rho 
## 0.5122324

So, we have decent agreement between the GMPU and Elo scores for levels. Its medium, but significant. However, the general recollection was that GMPU was highly correlated with the mean duration to solve a level. Thats next.

Elo Compared with External Measures

There are multiple angles I want to look at with the duration values. Ive pulled out the mean duration (in seconds) spent {playing each level (mean_Dur_total), the mean duration spent to solve a level (mean_Dur_solved), and the mean duration spent on levels left unsolved (mean_Dur_unsolved).

I am also including, here and there, the total number of times a level was played, solved, and left unsolved (\(n_{unsolved} + n_{solved} = n_{played}\)).

level_data %>% 
  select(n_unsolved:gmpu) %>% 
    cor(., use = 'complete.obs', 
      method = 'spearman') %>% 
  round(., 3)

n_unsolved

So looking across the Elo and GMPU rows, it is particularly interesting to see that Elo is more strongly correlated with the number of times a level is left unsolved (\(\rho\) = 0.4) compared to GMPU (\(\rho\) = -0.12). Assuming that players are more likely to leave harder levels unsolved, this is a positive merit for Elo over GMPU. We would expect the number of unsolved levels to increase and the difficulty increased. This is the case with Elo. But with GMPU there is barely any relation.

However, there is very little difference between the total number of times a level was played and the number of times it was solved.

level_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = elo, 
             y = n_unsolved, 
             label = level)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_label_repel(max.overlaps = 10) +
  labs (
    title = "Elo")

level_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = gmpu, 
             y = n_unsolved, 
             label = level)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_label_repel(max.overlaps = 10) +
  labs (
    title = "GMPU")

Looking at the two scatterplots above, the tutorial levels are creating some noise in the data. Removing them is likely warranted, but I dont have a concrete list of which levels were used as tutorial levels in either study. Im fairly certain Down HIll, Lever, and the other in that group and Nudge are. But Ill wait until I can confirm to remove them.

Either way, Im looking at number of times a level is left unsolved as a proxy of level difficulty because of the assumption that harders levels are more often left unsolved. Tutorial levels are an exception. These are levels that are more often skipped simply because they are too easy or just shown when the game is first loaded. Therefore, I would anticipate removing tutorial levels would only improve the correlation between Elo and n_unsolved.

Mean Duration on SOLVED levels

Across the mean duration variables Elo and GMPU are nearly identically correlated with duration variable. And Elo has a consistently high correlation with duration variables than GMPU (by about 0.142). The mean duration to solve a level is most interesting. The mean duration spent on unsolved levels likely has a slight negative skew due to levels that are left unsolved without genuine effort to solve. I am already confident about the correlation above, but still want to see the scatterplot and add the n_unsolved for comparison.

The below scatterplot shows the relationship between Elo and the mean duration to solve a level. The duration variable for this graphic is log transformed. The color gradient is the number of times the level was left unsolved. Lighter colors indicate greater times a level was left unsolved. It is fairly clear that levels on the far right and left are much lighter than the center cluster. The lower points with lighter color are the tutorial levels, so this is another indication that tutorial levels need to be dropped. The very light blue level in the center of the plot is Nudge.

level_data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = elo, 
             y = log(mean_Dur_solved), 
             label = level, 
             color = n_unsolved)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_label_repel(max.overlaps = 15) +
  labs(
    title = 'Elo v. Mean Duration to Solve',
    x = 'Level Elo Score (based on both studies)',
    y = 'Mean Duration to Solve (log transformed)'
  ) + ylim(1,7)
